31. Comparison Operators
Definition

Comparison operators are used in SQL to compare two values. They are commonly used in the WHERE clause to filter records.

Common Comparison Operators
Operator	Meaning
=	Equal to
!= or <>	Not equal to
>	Greater than
<	Less than
>=	Greater than or equal to
<=	Less than or equal to
Syntax
SELECT column_name
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name operator value;
Example
SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE Salary > 50000;

Output

EmpID	Name	Salary
102	Priya	60000
103	Aman	70000
32. Logical Operators
Definition

Logical operators combine multiple conditions in SQL.

Types
AND
OR
NOT
Syntax
SELECT *
FROM table_name
WHERE condition1 AND condition2;
Example
SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE Salary > 50000
AND Department = 'IT';

Only employees satisfying both conditions are returned.

33. BETWEEN
Definition

The BETWEEN operator selects values within a given range.

The range is inclusive, meaning both the start and end values are included.

Syntax
SELECT *
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name BETWEEN value1 AND value2;
Example
SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE Salary BETWEEN 30000 AND 50000;

Output

Name	Salary
Rahul	35000
Aman	50000
34. IN
Definition

The IN operator checks whether a value matches any value in a list.

It is a shorter alternative to multiple OR conditions.

Syntax
SELECT *
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name IN (value1, value2, value3);
Example
SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE Department IN ('HR', 'IT');

Equivalent to

SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE Department = 'HR'
OR Department = 'IT';
35. LIKE
Definition

The LIKE operator is used to search for a specific pattern in a column.

It works together with wildcards.

Syntax
SELECT *
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name LIKE pattern;
Example

Names starting with A

SELECT *
FROM Students
WHERE Name LIKE 'A%';

Output

Name
Aman
Anjali
36. Wildcards
Definition

Wildcards are special characters used with the LIKE operator to search for patterns.

Common Wildcards
Wildcard	Meaning
%	Zero or more characters
_	Exactly one character
Syntax
SELECT *
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name LIKE pattern;
Examples
Starts with A
SELECT *
FROM Students
WHERE Name LIKE 'A%';

Matches

Aman
Anjali
Akash
Ends with a
SELECT *
FROM Students
WHERE Name LIKE '%a';

Matches

Priya
Anusha
Contains "it"
SELECT *
FROM Students
WHERE Name LIKE '%it%';

Matches

Nitin
Aditi
Second letter is "a"
SELECT *
FROM Students
WHERE Name LIKE '_a%';

Matches

Rahul
Karan
37. IS NULL / IS NOT NULL
Definition

IS NULL checks for missing values.

IS NOT NULL checks for existing values.

Never use

WHERE Phone = NULL

Always use

WHERE Phone IS NULL
Syntax

Find NULL values

SELECT *
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name IS NULL;

Find non-NULL values

SELECT *
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name IS NOT NULL;
Example
SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE Email IS NULL;

Returns employees whose email is unknown.

38. AND vs OR
Definition
AND

Returns rows only if all conditions are true.

OR

Returns rows if at least one condition is true.

Syntax
AND
SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE Salary > 50000
AND Department='IT';
OR
SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE Department='HR'
OR Department='Sales';
Example

Table

Name	Department	Salary
Rahul	IT	60000
Priya	HR	45000
Aman	IT	40000
AND
SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE Department='IT'
AND Salary>50000;

Output

Name
Rahul
OR
SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE Department='HR'
OR Salary>50000;

Output

Name
Rahul
Priya
39. Aliases
Definition

An alias is a temporary name given to a column or table to make SQL queries easier to read.

The keyword AS is optional.

Syntax
Column Alias
SELECT column_name AS alias_name
FROM table_name;
Table Alias
SELECT *
FROM table_name AS t;
Example

Column Alias

SELECT Name AS Employee_Name,
Salary AS Monthly_Salary
FROM Employee;

Output

Employee_Name	Monthly_Salary
Rahul	50000

Table Alias

SELECT e.Name
FROM Employee AS e;
40. CASE Statement
Definition

The CASE statement is used to perform conditional logic in SQL.

It works similarly to an if-else statement in programming languages.

Syntax
SELECT column_name,
CASE
    WHEN condition1 THEN result1
    WHEN condition2 THEN result2
    ELSE result
END AS alias_name
FROM table_name;
Example
SELECT Name,
Salary,
CASE
    WHEN Salary >= 60000 THEN 'High Salary'
    WHEN Salary >= 40000 THEN 'Medium Salary'
    ELSE 'Low Salary'
END AS Salary_Category
FROM Employee;

Output

Name	Salary	Salary_Category
Rahul	65000	High Salary
Priya	45000	Medium Salary
Aman	30000	Low Salary
